│                          │ parameter budget, this block adopts global (shared) ring entanglement via CRX around the  │
│                          │ board perimeter and a shared hub entanglement via CRY from the center to each edge. This  │
│                          │ reduces parameter count per block (11 keys vs 13 in the previous variant) and leverages   │
│                          │ structured symmetry: shared pre/post-RZ and shared RY layers preserve Tic-Tac-Toe board   │
│                          │ symmetries while the ring/hub interactions provide richer inter-qubit correlations        │
│                          │ without exploding the parameter budget. This mirrors the second program’s improvements    │
│                          │ (0.60 combined score) by collapsing ring and hub gates to single shared parameters,       │
│                          │ potentially improving generalization and convergence with Adam.                           │
