╭──────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
│ Field                    │ Value                                                                                     │
├──────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ patch_type               │ cross                                                                                     │
│ patch_name               │ hybrid_crx_crz_hub_ansatz                                                                 │
│ patch_description        │ This crossover combines the best aspects of three prior implementations:                  │
│                          │                                                                                           │
│                          │ 1. **From the first prior program (score 0.57)**: Uses shared `crz_hub_edge` parameter    │
│                          │ for all center-to-edge CRZ gates, which reduces parameter count to 60 while maintaining   │
│                          │ expressiveness through parameter sharing by symmetry.                                     │
│                          │                                                                                           │
│                          │ 2. **From the second prior program (score 0.60)**: Replaces the ring CZ gates with        │
│                          │ parametrized CRX gates using a shared `crx_ring` parameter. This adds learnable           │
│                          │ entanglement on the outer ring, which improved validation accuracy to 0.65.               │
│                          │                                                                                           │
│                          │ 3. **From the current program (score 0.55)**: Uses distinct per-edge hub parameters       │
│                          │ (`crz_hub_edge_0` through `crz_hub_edge_3`), which provides more flexibility but at the   │
│                          │ cost of more parameters (78).                                                             │
│                          │                                                                                           │
│                          │ **Crossover strategy**: Combine the parametrized ring entanglement (CRX with shared       │
│                          │ parameter) from the second program with the shared hub entanglement (single               │
│                          │ `crz_hub_edge` parameter) from the first program. This hybrid approach aims to:           │
│                          │ - Keep parameter count moderate (around 66-72 parameters)                                 │
│                          │ - Leverage learnable ring entanglement which showed promise (validation accuracy 0.65)    │
│                          │ - Maintain parameter efficiency through sharing on the hub layer                          │
│                          │ - Balance expressiveness with generalization                                              │
│                          │                                                                                           │
│                          │ The resulting ansatz has:                                                                 │
│                          │ - Pre/post RZ rotations with symmetry-based sharing (6 unique parameters)                 │
│                          │ - RY rotations with symmetry-based sharing (3 unique parameters)                          │
│                          │ - Parametrized CRX ring with one shared parameter (1 parameter)                           │
│                          │ - Shared CRZ hub entanglement (1 parameter)                                               │
│                          │ - Total: 11 parameters per block × 6 blocks = 66 parameters                               │
│                          │                                                                                           │
│                          │ This should improve upon the current score of 0.55 by combining validated improvements    │
│                          │ from higher-scoring candidates.                                                           │
